    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-09-08T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-09-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="78"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d78">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.<gloss target="#t_BC1">BC</gloss>/9–848:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Norway</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Oslo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-09-08T23:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 8, 1948—11 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>588. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 425, September 3 [<hi
                        rend="italic">2</hi>]. I questioned Foreign Minister yesterday regarding
                    Norwegian attitude toward acceptance seat on Security Council. Lange replied
                    matter had been discussed and that government had reached decision to accept
                    seat. It is probable Lange will make gesture of informing Unden and Rasmussen in
                    Stockholm of Norwegian intention but there is no indication that Lange
                    anticipates any objection from Sweden or Denmark.</p>
                <p>Subsequent to <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 526, August 6, Counselor
                    discussed matter with Secretary-General Foreign Office, who intimated Norwegians
                    had reluctantly made up mind to accept seat despite added burden and personnel
                    difficulties. He said British had already approached them along the lines <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 425, September 3 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >2</hi>].</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
